<subSubSection lastPageId="15" lastPageNumber="392" pageId="14" pageNumber="391" type="distribution">
<paragraph blockId="14.[151,1437,1734,2013]" pageId="14" pageNumber="391">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[151,307,1734,1760]" pageId="14" pageNumber="391">Distribution:</emphasis>
Widely distributed from southern 
<collectingCountry box="[693,781,1735,1761]" name="Mexico" pageId="14" pageNumber="391">México</collectingCountry>
, across Central America, and northwestern South America in 
<collectingCountry box="[180,290,1771,1797]" name="Colombia" pageId="14" pageNumber="391">Colombia</collectingCountry>
and north 
<collectingCountry box="[411,533,1771,1797]" name="Venezuela" pageId="14" pageNumber="391">Venezuela</collectingCountry>
. In 
<collectingCountry box="[573,683,1771,1797]" name="Colombia" pageId="14" pageNumber="391">Colombia</collectingCountry>
either in the trans- and cis-Andean region (
<figureCitation box="[1171,1259,1771,1797]" captionStart="FIGURE 4" captionStartId="4.[151,250,1888,1912]" captionTargetBox="[217,1370,181,1864]" captionTargetId="figure-22@4.[217,1370,181,1864]" captionTargetPageId="4" captionText="FIGURE 4. Distribution maps for the cis-Andean microteiid lizards in Colombia (Alopoglossidae + Gymnophthalmidae). Circles are examined specimens, while squares are records from literature (see Supplementary Files for specific references). Red arrows indicate new records for Colombia. Black arrows show a zoom in to regions where several records overlap. The light green shadow indicates the Orinoco River basin, and the dark green the Amazon River basin." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5681929" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5681929/files/figure.png" pageId="14" pageNumber="391">Fig. 4E</figureCitation>
).
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="14.[151,1437,1734,2013]" lastBlockId="15.[151,1437,151,465]" lastPageId="15" lastPageNumber="392" pageId="14" pageNumber="391">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,389,1806,1832]" pageId="14" pageNumber="391">Similar species:</emphasis>
Unfortunately, the morphological characters discussed in the literature are not completely conclusive to differentiate individuals of the cis-Andean 
<taxonomicName baseAuthorityName="Hallowell" baseAuthorityYear="1861" box="[800,1113,1843,1869]" class="Reptilia" family="Gymnophthalmidae" genus="Gymnophthalmus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Squamata" pageId="14" pageNumber="391" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="speciosus">
<emphasis box="[800,1113,1843,1869]" italics="true" pageId="14" pageNumber="391">Gymnophthalmus speciosus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
group from other sympatric congenerics. However, according to different bibliographical sources, 
<taxonomicName baseAuthorityName="Hallowell" baseAuthorityYear="1861" box="[952,1096,1879,1905]" class="Reptilia" family="Gymnophthalmidae" genus="Gymnophthalmus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Squamata" pageId="14" pageNumber="391" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="speciosus">
<emphasis box="[952,1096,1879,1905]" italics="true" pageId="14" pageNumber="391">G. speciosus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
group may differ in having a reddish tail (blue in 
<taxonomicName box="[375,491,1915,1941]" class="Reptilia" family="Gymnophthalmidae" genus="Gymnophthalmus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Squamata" pageId="14" pageNumber="391" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="cryptus">
<emphasis box="[375,491,1915,1941]" italics="true" pageId="14" pageNumber="391">G. cryptus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, grey in 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Vanzolini &amp; Carvalho" authorityYear="1991" box="[589,761,1915,1941]" class="Reptilia" family="Gymnophthalmidae" genus="Gymnophthalmus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Squamata" pageId="14" pageNumber="391" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="leucomystax">
<emphasis box="[589,761,1915,1941]" italics="true" pageId="14" pageNumber="391">G. leucomystax</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, and salmon-pink in 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Garcia-Perez &amp; Schargel" authorityYear="2017" box="[996,1181,1915,1941]" class="Reptilia" family="Gymnophthalmidae" genus="Gymnophthalmus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Squamata" pageId="14" pageNumber="391" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="marconaterai">
<emphasis box="[996,1181,1915,1941]" italics="true" pageId="14" pageNumber="391">G. marconaterai</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
); upper lip cream with dark spots or dark brown (white in 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Vanzolini &amp; Carvalho" authorityYear="1991" box="[551,724,1951,1977]" class="Reptilia" family="Gymnophthalmidae" genus="Gymnophthalmus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Squamata" pageId="14" pageNumber="391" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="leucomystax">
<emphasis box="[551,724,1951,1977]" italics="true" pageId="14" pageNumber="391">G. leucomystax</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
and 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Garcia-Perez &amp; Schargel" authorityYear="2017" box="[781,967,1951,1977]" class="Reptilia" family="Gymnophthalmidae" genus="Gymnophthalmus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Squamata" pageId="14" pageNumber="391" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="marconaterai">
<emphasis box="[781,967,1951,1977]" italics="true" pageId="14" pageNumber="391">G. marconaterai</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
); cream belly with dark spots (dark in 
<taxonomicName class="Reptilia" family="Gymnophthalmidae" genus="Gymnophthalmus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Squamata" pageId="14" pageNumber="391" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="cryptus">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="14" pageNumber="391">G. cryptus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, white in 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Vanzolini &amp; Carvalho" authorityYear="1991" box="[347,520,1987,2013]" class="Reptilia" family="Gymnophthalmidae" genus="Gymnophthalmus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Squamata" pageId="14" pageNumber="391" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="leucomystax">
<emphasis box="[347,520,1987,2013]" italics="true" pageId="14" pageNumber="391">G. leucomystax</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
and 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Garcia-Perez &amp; Schargel" authorityYear="2017" box="[576,762,1987,2013]" class="Reptilia" family="Gymnophthalmidae" genus="Gymnophthalmus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Squamata" pageId="14" pageNumber="391" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="marconaterai">
<emphasis box="[576,762,1987,2013]" italics="true" pageId="14" pageNumber="391">G. marconaterai</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
); inconspicuous dorsolateral stripe that fades away towards the midbody (vivid dorsolateral stripe that extends from the supraocular region to the base of the tail in 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Vanzolini &amp; Carvalho" authorityYear="1991" class="Reptilia" family="Gymnophthalmidae" genus="Gymnophthalmus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Squamata" pageId="15" pageNumber="392" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="leucomystax">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="15" pageNumber="392">G. leucomystax</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, and extends towards the posterior region of the tail in 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Garcia-Perez &amp; Schargel" authorityYear="2017" box="[869,1056,187,213]" class="Reptilia" family="Gymnophthalmidae" genus="Gymnophthalmus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Squamata" pageId="15" pageNumber="392" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="marconaterai">
<emphasis box="[869,1056,187,213]" italics="true" pageId="15" pageNumber="392">G. marconaterai</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
); and in normally possessing 13, rarely 15, scales around midbody (15, rarely 14, in 
<taxonomicName box="[728,844,223,249]" class="Reptilia" family="Gymnophthalmidae" genus="Gymnophthalmus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Squamata" pageId="15" pageNumber="392" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="cryptus">
<emphasis box="[728,844,223,249]" italics="true" pageId="15" pageNumber="392">G. cryptus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
). For more detailed descriptions see 
<bibRefCitation author="Hernandez-Ruz, E. J." pageId="15" pageNumber="392" pagination="79 - 88" refId="ref16878" refString="Hernandez-Ruz, E. J. (2006) Gymnophthalmus speciosus (Hallowell, 1861) (Squamata, Gymnophthalmidae) in Colombia. Caldasia, 28 (1), 79 - 88." type="journal article" year="2006">Hernández-Ruz (2006)</bibRefCitation>
, 
<bibRefCitation author="Recoder, R. &amp; Dal Vechio, F. &amp; Marques-Sousa, S. &amp; Teixeira, M. &amp; Silva-Da-Silva, M. &amp; Santos-Jr., A. P. &amp; Ribeiro, S. &amp; Barrio-Amoros, C. &amp; Rodrigues, M. T." box="[240,478,259,285]" pageId="15" pageNumber="392" pagination="61 - 81" refId="ref18267" refString="Recoder, R., Dal Vechio, F., Marques-Sousa, S., Teixeira, M., Silva-Da-Silva, M., Santos-Jr., A. P., Ribeiro, S., Barrio-Amoros, C. &amp; Rodrigues, M. T. (2018) Geographic variation and taxonomy of red-tailed Gymnophthalmus (Squamata: Gymnophthalmidae) from Amazonian Savannas. Zootaxa, 4497 (1), 61 - 81. https: // doi. org / 10.11646 / zootaxa. 4497.1.4" type="journal article" year="2018">
Recoder 
<emphasis box="[340,396,259,285]" italics="true" pageId="15" pageNumber="392">et al.</emphasis>
(2018)
</bibRefCitation>
and 
<bibRefCitation author="Senaris, J. C. &amp; Aristeguieta-Padron, M. M. &amp; Rojas, H. &amp; Rojas-Runjaic F. J. M." box="[532,762,259,285]" pageId="15" pageNumber="392" refId="ref19176" refString="Senaris, J. C., Aristeguieta-Padron, M. M., Rojas, H. &amp; Rojas-Runjaic F. J. M. (2018) Guia ilustrada de los anfibios y reptiles del valle de Caracas, Venezuela. Instituto Venezolano de Investigaciones Cientificas, Caracas, 348 pp." type="book" year="2018">
Señaris 
<emphasis box="[622,678,259,285]" italics="true" pageId="15" pageNumber="392">et al.</emphasis>
(2018)
</bibRefCitation>
.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="15" pageNumber="392" type="discussion">
<paragraph blockId="15.[151,1437,151,465]" pageId="15" pageNumber="392">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,317,295,321]" pageId="15" pageNumber="392">Remarks:</emphasis>
Deeper phylogenetic and morphological analyses are needed to properly elucidate the evolutionary relationships within the genus and its possible hidden diversity. The 
<typeStatus box="[939,987,331,357]" pageId="15" pageNumber="392">type</typeStatus>
locality of 
<taxonomicName baseAuthorityName="Hallowell" baseAuthorityYear="1861" box="[1122,1436,331,357]" class="Reptilia" family="Gymnophthalmidae" genus="Gymnophthalmus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Squamata" pageId="15" pageNumber="392" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="speciosus">
<emphasis box="[1122,1436,331,357]" italics="true" pageId="15" pageNumber="392">Gymnophthalmus speciosus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is in 
<collectingCountry box="[207,325,367,393]" name="Nicaragua" pageId="15" pageNumber="392">Nicaragua</collectingCountry>
, and it is possible that Middle American and eastern South American populations belong to different entities, but currently there are no known diagnostic characters to separate them (
<bibRefCitation author="Vanzolini, P. E. &amp; de Carvalho, C. M." box="[1115,1431,403,429]" pageId="15" pageNumber="392" pagination="173 - 226" refId="ref19784" refString="Vanzolini, P. E. &amp; de Carvalho, C. M. (1991) Two sibling and sympatric species of Gymnophthalmus in Roraima, Brasil (Sauria: Teiidae). Papeis Avulsos de Zoologia, Sao Paulo, 37 (12), 173 - 226." type="journal article" year="1991">Vanzolini &amp; Carvalho 1991</bibRefCitation>
; 
<bibRefCitation author="Recoder, R. &amp; Dal Vechio, F. &amp; Marques-Sousa, S. &amp; Teixeira, M. &amp; Silva-Da-Silva, M. &amp; Santos-Jr., A. P. &amp; Ribeiro, S. &amp; Barrio-Amoros, C. &amp; Rodrigues, M. T." box="[151,375,439,465]" pageId="15" pageNumber="392" pagination="61 - 81" refId="ref18267" refString="Recoder, R., Dal Vechio, F., Marques-Sousa, S., Teixeira, M., Silva-Da-Silva, M., Santos-Jr., A. P., Ribeiro, S., Barrio-Amoros, C. &amp; Rodrigues, M. T. (2018) Geographic variation and taxonomy of red-tailed Gymnophthalmus (Squamata: Gymnophthalmidae) from Amazonian Savannas. Zootaxa, 4497 (1), 61 - 81. https: // doi. org / 10.11646 / zootaxa. 4497.1.4" type="journal article" year="2018">
Recoder 
<emphasis box="[251,301,439,465]" italics="true" pageId="15" pageNumber="392">et al</emphasis>
. 2018
</bibRefCitation>
).
</paragraph>
